export const meta = {
  name: 'review-pr34-attachment',
  description: 'Deep review of yandex-tracker-mcp PR #34 (issue_add_attachment): API compliance, security, architecture, quality, tests — adversarially verified',
  phases: [
    { title: 'Review', detail: 'parallel lenses: security, API, architecture/quality, tests' },
    { title: 'Verify', detail: 'adversarially verify each candidate finding against the actual code' },
  ],
}

const REPO = 'aikts/yandex-tracker-mcp'
const CWD = '/Volumes/Workspace/Projects/_/ai/mcp/mcp-yandex-tracker'

// First-hand verified facts to ground the agents (do NOT let them re-derive these wrong):
const CONTEXT = `
You are reviewing GitHub PR #${'34'} on repo ${REPO}. The local checkout of the SAME repo is at ${CWD} (base branch 'main'; the PR is NOT checked out locally, so read the diff from GitHub).

Get the diff by running:  gh pr diff 34 --repo ${REPO}
Read supporting code from the local repo at ${CWD} with Read/rg (the base 'main' version — close enough; the PR only ADDS a method).

What the PR does: adds an 'issue_add_attachment' MCP write tool. The tool takes a server-side 'file_path' (and optional 'filename'), does Path(file_path).read_bytes(), and POSTs it as multipart/form-data field 'file' to v3/issues/{id}/attachments/.

VERIFIED FACTS (already confirmed first-hand — treat as ground truth, do not contradict without strong evidence):
- Official Yandex Tracker API (yandex.ru/support/tracker post-attachment): POST https://api.tracker.yandex.net/v3/issues/<id>/attachments/ (WITH trailing slash); multipart/form-data; file field name is 'file'; 'filename' is an OPTIONAL QUERY parameter for the stored name; max size 1024 MB; success = 201. => The PR's endpoint, trailing slash, and 'file' field name are CORRECT.
- The PR sets the override name via the multipart part's Content-Disposition filename (aiohttp FormData.add_field("file", content, filename=...)), NOT via the documented ?filename= query param. The curl example in the docs (--form 'file=@/path/image.png') implies the part filename is used as the stored name, so this likely works, but it does not follow the documented contract.
- TrackerClient is constructed in mcp_tracker/mcp/server.py WITHOUT a timeout arg, so it uses the default ClientTimeout(total=10) — a 10-second TOTAL timeout on every request, not configurable via Settings (no timeout setting exists). This applies to the upload too.
- The server supports remote transports: Settings.transport ∈ {stdio, sse, streamable-http}, plus OAuth multi-tenant mode (oauth_enabled, mcp_server_public_url). So 'remote deployment' is a first-class, supported scenario, not hypothetical.
- check_issue_access only checks the queue prefix against TRACKER_LIMIT_QUEUES; it does NOT validate file_path.
`

const FINDINGS_SCHEMA = {
  type: 'object',
  properties: {
    findings: {
      type: 'array',
      items: {
        type: 'object',
        properties: {
          title: { type: 'string' },
          severity: { type: 'string', enum: ['critical', 'high', 'medium', 'low', 'nit'] },
          location: { type: 'string', description: 'file:line or function/area' },
          explanation: { type: 'string', description: 'what is wrong and the concrete impact' },
          recommendation: { type: 'string' },
        },
        required: ['title', 'severity', 'location', 'explanation', 'recommendation'],
      },
    },
  },
  required: ['findings'],
}

const VERDICT_SCHEMA = {
  type: 'object',
  properties: {
    verdict: { type: 'string', enum: ['confirmed', 'partly', 'refuted'] },
    adjusted_severity: { type: 'string', enum: ['critical', 'high', 'medium', 'low', 'nit'] },
    reasoning: { type: 'string', description: 'cite the exact code/behavior that confirms or refutes; note any overstatement' },
  },
  required: ['verdict', 'adjusted_severity', 'reasoning'],
}

const LENSES = [
  {
    key: 'security',
    prompt: `${CONTEXT}

LENS: SECURITY (this is the most important lens). The server can run REMOTELY (sse/streamable-http) and MULTI-TENANT (OAuth). Analyze 'issue_add_attachment' which does Path(file_path).read_bytes() on a caller-supplied path with NO validation.
Consider concretely:
- Arbitrary local file disclosure / exfiltration: can a remote MCP client (or the LLM driving it, possibly via prompt injection in issue text that THIS server fetches and feeds to the model) read arbitrary server files (/etc/passwd, /proc/self/environ which leaks TRACKER_TOKEN & OAUTH_ENCRYPTION_KEYS, .env, SSH keys, OTHER tenants' data) and upload them to an attacker-controlled issue? Trace the full chain.
- In OAuth multi-tenant mode the file path is server-side, so per-user auth is bypassed for file content (confused deputy). Assess.
- Path traversal / symlink following (no Path.resolve, no allow-root).
- DoS: unbounded read into memory; no size pre-check.
- Whether read-only mode or queue limits mitigate any of this (they don't gate file_path).
Propose concrete mitigations (base64 content over transport; opt-in setting; allowed-root dir + symlink resolution; disable for non-stdio/OAuth). Rate severity honestly for the remote scenario.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'api',
    prompt: `${CONTEXT}

LENS: YANDEX TRACKER API COMPLIANCE. Verify the client method against the verified facts. Check: endpoint/trailing slash, multipart field name 'file', the filename-as-query-param vs Content-Disposition discrepancy (does the override reliably set the stored name?), Content-Type handling (does _build_headers inject a conflicting Content-Type? does aiohttp set the multipart boundary?), status-code handling (201 success path, 404->IssueNotFound, other 4xx/5xx via raise_for_status), response parsing (IssueAttachment.model_validate_json). Flag anything that diverges from the documented API contract or from how the codebase calls other endpoints.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'arch',
    prompt: `${CONTEXT}

LENS: ARCHITECTURE & IMPLEMENTATION QUALITY (esp. for remote deployment). Check:
- Blocking I/O: Path.read_bytes() is a synchronous blocking call inside an async tool handler — does it block the event loop and stall all concurrent requests on a remote server? How should it be done (asyncio.to_thread / streaming)?
- The 10s total client timeout vs advertised 1024 MB uploads: will real uploads time out? Is there any way to raise the timeout? Is this a correctness defect for the feature's own purpose?
- Memory: whole file read into RAM then copied into the multipart body — impact at hundreds of MB.
- Layering/conventions vs CLAUDE.md: proto -> client -> caching passthrough -> tool. Is the caching passthrough correct (writes not cached)? Are signatures consistent (keyword-only content/filename, auth param)? Naming, error types (TrackerError vs IssueNotFound), docstrings.
- Tool annotations (readOnlyHint=False; any destructive/openWorld hints needed?), parameter typing/Field descriptions.
Rate each issue's severity.`,
  },
  {
    key: 'tests',
    prompt: `${CONTEXT}

LENS: TEST COVERAGE. Read the new tests (test_issue_attachments.py HTTP test, test_issues_protocol.py caching test, test_issue_write_tools.py MCP tool tests, test_server_creation.py WRITE_TOOL_NAMES). Assess what is and isn't covered. Specifically: does the HTTP test assert the actual multipart payload (field name 'file', the filename) so a regression in field name/filename wiring would be caught? Is the filename-as-query-param behavior tested? Size-limit enforcement? Blocking-read behavior? read-only-mode-not-registered test for this tool? Symlink/traversal? Note missing assertions and missing cases, and whether tests would catch the bugs other lenses find.`,
  },
]

phase('Review')
const results = await pipeline(
  LENSES,
  (lens) => agent(lens.prompt, { label: `review:${lens.key}`, phase: 'Review', schema: FINDINGS_SCHEMA, effort: 'high' }),
  (review, lens) =>
    parallel((review?.findings || []).map((f) => () =>
      agent(
        `${CONTEXT}\n\nAdversarially VERIFY this candidate review finding against the ACTUAL code (run gh pr diff 34 --repo ${REPO} and read the local repo). Default to skepticism: if the code does not actually do what the finding claims, mark refuted. If real but overstated (wrong severity/scope), mark partly and adjust. Confirm only if the code genuinely exhibits it.\n\nFINDING [${lens.key}] (claimed severity: ${f.severity}):\nTitle: ${f.title}\nLocation: ${f.location}\nExplanation: ${f.explanation}\nRecommendation: ${f.recommendation}`,
        { label: `verify:${lens.key}:${(f.title || '').slice(0, 30)}`, phase: 'Verify', schema: VERDICT_SCHEMA, effort: 'high' }
      ).then((v) => ({ lens: lens.key, finding: f, verdict: v }))
    ))
)

const flat = results.flat().filter(Boolean)
const kept = flat.filter((r) => r.verdict && r.verdict.verdict !== 'refuted')
const refuted = flat.filter((r) => r.verdict && r.verdict.verdict === 'refuted')

log(`Reviewed ${flat.length} candidate findings: ${kept.length} confirmed/partly, ${refuted.length} refuted`)

return {
  kept: kept.map((r) => ({
    lens: r.lens,
    title: r.finding.title,
    claimed_severity: r.finding.severity,
    adjusted_severity: r.verdict.adjusted_severity,
    verdict: r.verdict.verdict,
    location: r.finding.location,
    explanation: r.finding.explanation,
    recommendation: r.finding.recommendation,
    verify_reasoning: r.verdict.reasoning,
  })),
  refuted: refuted.map((r) => ({ lens: r.lens, title: r.finding.title, why: r.verdict.reasoning })),
}
